A security scanner runs as part of a CI/CD pipeline and must decide whether to block a merge based on its findings. This is the security gate problem: a binary pass/fail decision that has consequences for both security (blocking merges allows vulnerabilities to be caught before production) and development velocity (blocking merges on false positives or low-severity findings creates friction and erodes developer trust).

Reason carefully through the design of a security gate policy that is defensible, calibrated, and sustainable in a team of 5-20 developers:

The blocking threshold problem: should the gate block on any CRITICAL finding, any CRITICAL or HIGH finding, any finding above a configurable threshold, or only on findings that are new (not present in the baseline)? Reason through the security and velocity implications of each policy, including the game-theoretic consideration that developers will find workarounds (inline suppressions, committing pre-analysed stubs) if the gate is too aggressive.

The baseline problem: a codebase acquired from a third party or migrated from legacy has 500 existing findings. Should the gate block on all of them immediately, block only on regressions (new findings introduced in this PR), or use a ratchet approach (the finding count can never increase, but does not have to decrease immediately)? What are the security risks of the ratchet approach — specifically, does it allow the debt to grow if existing findings are suppressed and new ones are introduced at the same rate?

The suppression governance problem: developers will need to suppress false positives. What suppression mechanism minimises abuse (suppressing true positives)? Options include: inline comment suppression (noqa-style), a central suppression registry, requiring security team approval for suppressions, or time-limited suppressions that expire and re-trigger. What are the operational costs and security benefits of each?

The flaky finding problem: some vulnerability categories (race conditions, certain SSRF patterns) have non-deterministic detection due to file ordering or non-deterministic AST traversal. How should a security gate handle findings that appear and disappear between runs on the same code?

Produce a concrete gate policy recommendation with specific thresholds, suppression rules, and escalation paths.
